Sometimes "{{lang|zh|士}}" ''shì'' is used instead of "{{lang|zh|四}}" ''sì''. Sometimes "{{lang|zh|一}}" ''yī'' is not used, or its role is exchanged with "{{lang|zh|乙}}" ''yǐ''.

To represent other notes in different [[octave]]s, traditions differ among themselves. For ''[[Kunqu]]'', the end strokes of "{{lang|zh|上}}" "{{lang|zh|尺}}" "{{lang|zh|工}}" "{{lang|zh|凡}}" are extended by a tiny slash downward for the lower octave, a [[radical (Chinese character)|radical]] "{{lang|zh|亻}}" is added for one octave higher than the central. For [[Cantonese opera]], however, "{{lang|zh|亻}}" means an octave lower, while "{{lang|zh|彳}}" means an octave higher.

Some other variations:
* "{{lang|zh|尺}}" is replaced by "{{lang|zh|乂}}" in Taiwanese tradition.
* "{{lang|zh|凡}}" is replaced by "{{lang|zh|反}}" in Cantonese tradition.
* "{{lang|zh|彳上}}", the "do" just above the central octave, is usually replaced by "{{lang|zh|生}}" in Cantonese tradition.

