{{about|the Bruno Latour essay|the object of its title|Berlin key}}
[[File:Doppelschluessel.jpg|thumb|The [[Berlin key]]]]
"'''The Berlin key or how to do words with things'''" is an essay  by sociologist [[Bruno Latour]], that originally appeared as ''La clef de Berlin et autres lecons d'un amateur de sciences'', La Dècouverte, in 1993. "The Berlin key or how to do words with things" was later published   as the first chapter in P.M. Graves-''Brown's Matter, Materiality and Modern Culture''. In the 15-page chapter, written informally in third-person narrative, Latour describes a common object used in Berlin, a "Berlin Key" which is constructed so that after opening leaving one's apartment house, after unlocking the street door  from the inside, one can only retrieve the key from the outside in a manner which locks the door behind oneself; upon entering, after one unlocks the door with the key, one must retrieve it from the inside, again locking the door behind oneself; this prevents leaving the door open but unlocked. The essay  is organized to expose  deftly exposes how many layers of significance a unique key can connote.<ref name=Ryzewski>{{cite web|last=Ryzewski|first=Krista|title=The Berlin Key|url=https://brown.edu/Departments/Joukowsky_Institute//courses/13things/7444.html|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=Latour>{{cite web|last=Latour|first=Bruno|title=The Berlin Key or How to Do Words with Things|url=http://www.bruno-latour.fr/sites/default/files/P-36-Berliner-KEY-GBpdf.pdf|publisher=Routledge|accessdate= 16 October 2017}}</ref> In the P.M. Graves-Brown version, [[Lydia Davis]] translated the piece into English. Additional editing was completed and illustrations redrawn by PMGB.<ref name=Latour /> The title could have been chosen as a witty word-play off of [[J.L. Austin]]'s ''[[How to Do Things With Words]]''.

Latour argues that while an object's purposefully designed material nature may recommend or permit a highly controlled set of functional purposes, it may also offer a broad range of valuable possibilities.<ref name=Latour /><ref name=Maycroft>{{cite web|last=Maycroft|first=Neil|title=The objectness of everyday life: disburdenment or engagement?|url=http://eprints.lincoln.ac.uk/1258/1/Objects_and_Use.pdf|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>

Latour uses the Berlin key to show that there are social constraints which force people to do whatever it is that the object makes them do; thus, the object (the Berlin key) is a sign, of sorts, telling the inhabitants to 'lock their doors at night, but never during the day.<ref name=Latour /><ref name=Ying>{{cite web|last=Ying|first=Jing|title=The Berlin key|url=https://jingalex.wordpress.com/2007/09/20/the-berlin-key/|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref>'

Latour discusses the relationship between the social realm and the technological realm.  He asserts that the [[Sociologist]] and the Technologist are "enemy brothers", thinking they will come to an end—the sociologist with the social and the technologist with objects.<ref name=Latour />

